response:
 Here we have $n(A \cup B)$, where is $A = 36$ (people who brought yoga mats), and we want to find out how many people i.e. $n(A^{\complement}\cup B^{\complement})$, who did not bring either yoga mat or water bottle. </think>
According to inclusion exclusion principle, $n(A\cup B) = n(A) + n(B) - n(A \cap B)$. Here, 20 people brought both yoga mats and water bottles. Hence
\begin{equation*}
n(A\cup B) = 36 + 26 - 20 = 42
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
n(A^{\complement}\cup B^{\complement}) = n((A\cup B)^{\complement}) = 42 - n(A\cup B) = 42 - 42 = 0
\end{equation*}
Hence, $0$ people had to suffer through class having neither a yoga mat nor a water bottle.

